But they presently appear to be in heaven. —Ego tibi dico: note the vulgar emphasis—tot annis: apparently the ablative of time instead of the accusative of duration was com- moner in the sermo vulqaris than in literature. It is usual on plebeian tombstones. That Fever's constancy had early under- mined Claudius's health is recorded by Suetonius (Claud. 2 and 31). —Luguduni natus: cf. Suet. Claud. 2 and Dio, LIV. 36. The campaign against the Germans had called Claudius's parents, Drusus and Antonia, to the north, 10 Rc. —Marci municipem: the text here is doubtful. The name Planci, from L. Munatius Plancus, one of the founders in 43 Rc. of the Roman colony at Lugudunum, has been substituted by some editors for Illarci. Mark Antony the triumvir has been suggested, coins bearing his name having been struck at Lugudunum while he had the govern- ment of Gaul.
